<h1>The Women Scientists of India</h1>
<h2>Biographical and Autobiographical Essays</h2>
<h3>Biographical Essays</h3>
<div class="left">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/janaki_ammal.jpg" alt="Image" title="E K Janaki Ammal"/><strong>E K Janaki Ammal (1897-1984)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">D.Sc. (1931, Michigan), Founder Fellow of the Indian Academy of Sciences. Winner of Padmashri Award. Was a renowned botanist and plant cytologist who made significant contributions to genetics, evolution, phytogeography and ethnobotany.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_right"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/janaki_ammal.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">Edavaleth Kakkat Janaki Ammal</a><br />(By C V Subramanian)</div>
<hr />
<div class="right">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/bhushanam.jpg" alt="Image" title="B Vijayalakshmi"/><strong>B Vijayalakshmi (1952-1985)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">Ph.D (1982, Madras). For her research she studied relativistic wave equations and their proportions. She expired on 12th May 1985 at the age of 33 due to cancer. She had 11 papers to her credit in international journals.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_left"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/Vijayalakshmi.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">A heroic struggle of a scientist with a cancer</a><br />(By T R Govindarajan)</div>
<hr />
<div class="left">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/asima.jpg" alt="Image" title="A Chatterjee"/><strong>A Chatterjee (1917-2006)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">First woman D.Sc. (1944, Calcutta), FASc, FNA, Khaira Professor of Chemistry, Calcutta University. Recipient of the Padma Bhushan. The numerous awards she won include S S Bhatnagar award, C V Raman award of the UGC, P C Ray award, Sisir K Mitra Lectureship and Dr G P Chatterjee Lectureship. First lady president of the Indian Science Congress, member of Rajya Sabha. Her area of interest was natural products with special reference to the medicinal chemistry.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_right"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/Chatterjee.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">Asima Chatterjee</a><br />(By S C Prakashi)</div>
<hr />
<div class="right">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/anandi.jpg" alt="Image" title="Anandibai Joshi"/><strong>Anandibai Joshi (1865-1887)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">Medicine (1885, Philadelphia), Anandibai Joshi, the first Hindu woman to obtain a medical degree in the Western hemisphere, was born Yamuna Joshi on March 31, 1865 in Poona, India. She was the first lady to complete medical eduacation in the USA. She died in Poona at an early age of 22.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_left"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/anandi.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">Anandi Gopal</a><br />(By Pooja Thakar)</div>
<hr />
<div class="left">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/iravati.jpg" alt="Image" title="Iravati Karve"/><strong>Iravati Karve (1905-1970)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">Ph.D. (1930, Berlin). This renowned anthropologist was the Head of the Department of Sociology and Anthropology at Deccan College. She presided over the Anthropology division of the National Science Congress in 1947. She wrote extensively on a wide variety of academic subjects and otherwise. Her writings include the highly acclaimed book 'Yuganta' which won the Sahitya Academy Award.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_right"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/Iravati.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">Not so quiet has flown the Iravati</a><br />(By Jai Nimbkar and Varsha Kelkar-Mane)</div>
<hr />
<div class="right">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/annamani.jpg" alt="Image" title="Anna Mani"/><strong>Anna Mani (1918-2001)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">FASc, FNA, Ph.D. (submitted 1945, Madras). The only woman scientist to work with C.V. Raman, is well known for her work in atmospheric physics and instrumentation. She contributed to the study of radiation, ozone and atmospheric electricity, both on the surface and in the upper air using special sounding techniques. Joining the India Meteorological Department in 1948 she rose to become the Deputy Director General of Observatories in Delhi.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_left"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/annamani.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">An appreciation of Anna Mani</a><br />(By Abha Sur)</div>
<hr />
<div class="left">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/kamalranadive.jpg" alt="Image" title="Kamal Ranadive"/><strong>Kamal Ranadive (1917-2001)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">Ph.D. (1949, Bombay), FNA. This recipient of the Padmabhushan established the first tissue culture laboratory in India at the Indian Cancer Research Centre (presently Cancer Research Institute). She got Watumal Foundation Award for her work in the field of leprosy. She founded the Indian Women Scientist Association (IWSA).</p>
</div>
<div class="more_right"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/kamalranadive.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">Obsessed with excellence</a><br />(By Rajani Bhisey)</div>
<hr />
<div class="right">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/Darshan.jpg" alt="Image" title="Darshan Ranganathan"/><strong>Darshan Ranganathan (1941-2001)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">Ph.D. (1967, Delhi), FASc, FNA. Her honors include a Senior Research Scholarship of the Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851, A.V. Rama Rao Foundation Award, Jawaharlal Nehru Birth Centenary Visiting Fellowship, Third World Academy of Sciences Award in Chemistry and Sukh Dev Endowment Lectureship. Was Deputy Director, IICT, Hyderabad. She passed away from metastasis of cancer.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_left"><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/Darshan.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">She was a star</a><br />(By S Ranganathan)</div>
<hr />
<div class="left">
	<p><img src="<?=PUBLIC_URL?>images/stock/kamalasohonie.jpg" alt="Image" title="Kamala Sohonie"/><strong>Kamala Sohonie (1911-1996)</strong></p>
	<p class="info">Ph.D. (1939, Cambridge). Recipient of the Rastra-pati award for best scientific research. Life time achievement felicitation by ICMR. Assistant Director, NRI, Cunnoor, India. Retired as First Lady Director, Institute of Science, Mumbai.</p>
</div>
<div class="more_right"><strong>Article:</strong><a href="<?=RESOURCES_URL?>Initiatives/Women_in_Science/Contributors/kamalasohonie.pdf" title="read more" target="_blank">The scientist lady</a><br />(By Vasumathi Dhuru)</div>
<hr />
